<h2 id="why-real-estate">Why Diaspora Money Flows to Real Estate</h2>

<p>Real estate is the default investment for Ghanaians abroad. The logic feels unassailable: everyone needs housing, Ghana has a 1.8-million-unit housing deficit, property appreciates, and you end up with a tangible asset you can see on Google Maps.</p>

<p>This logic is correct in theory. In practice, real estate is where diaspora investors lose the most money, the most consistently, with the least recourse.</p>

<p>GhanaWorld scores the Affordable Housing and Construction Materials sector at 7.2/10. That score reflects genuine structural demand. It does not mean the sector is safe for remote investors. The gap between "this sector has real demand" and "I can profitably invest from abroad" is where fortunes disappear.</p>

